The "European Green Deal"
NEW YORK – Europe has led the way.
The "European Green Pact" announced by the European Commission is to date the first global sustainable development plan decided by a major region of the planet.
It has thus become a landmark for the whole world – a guide for the transition to a prosperous, socially inclusive, and environmentally sustainable economy, a first agenda, for all, to achieve it.
Naturally, the task awaiting the Europeans is daunting.
Even reading the documents that have just been made public appears to be a lavish one, at first glance, of plans, consultations, regulatory frameworks, laws, budgets, and diplomacy, a large number of involved and interconnected subjects, ranging from energy to transport, from food to industry.
Its detractors will mock European bureaucracy.
But it's a bureaucracy in the best Weberian sense of the term: it is rational.
The sustainable development objectives are clearly stated, the targets are defined in accordance with objectives subject to a deadline, and the programs and procedures are adapted to the targets.
In general, the ambition displayed is to achieve "carbon neutrality" (net zero greenhouse gas emissions) by 2050, to establish a circular economy that puts an end to the destructive pollution caused by plastics and other petrochemical derivatives, pesticides, and toxic waste, to establish a "from farm to table" food system that does not kill people by making them eat overly industrially transformed products, nor kill the earth with unsustainable agricultural practices.
And the European Commission understands that the method to achieve this must rely on the citizens themselves.
Again, the detractors will consider the announcements of public consultations as empty words for dreamers.
But go talk about unnecessary chatter to French President Emmanuel Macron, who has faced more than a year of manifestations turning into riots, or to Chilean President Sebastián Piñera, whose country suddenly rose up this fall after a slight increase in the price of subway tickets.
Macron and Piñera are both convinced of the need for environmental change.
Both have committed to carbon neutrality in their countries by 2050.
And both are desperately looking for ways to organize or structure public consultations, but after the fact.
American neoliberals will again mock and claim that the "market" will know how to remedy climate change.
But it's only a matter of looking at the United States today.
If neoliberals treat the planet the way they have treated American infrastructure, we all have reason to worry.
Arriving at an airport in the United States is to have to deal with malfunctioning elevators, escalators, shuttles, taxis that don't show up, rail links that don't exist, highways with roads in such poor condition that one cannot circulate, replaced by detours.
The reason for these dysfunctions is simple: corruption.
Each American electoral cycle costs today 8 billion dollars, if not more, and it is financed by billionaires, by major oil companies, the military-industrial complex, the healthcare industry lobby, and by interest groups determined to lower taxes and protect at all costs the status quo.
The solutions brought by the market are a farce when politics is subject to all the influences that emanate from it, as is the case in the United States.
The European Green Pact shows a government as it should be and not a government subordinate to business interests.
The European Green Deal actually provides a demonstration of the success of European social democracy (in its operational and not narrowly partisan sense).
An economy that combines markets, the state's regulatory power, the public sector, and civil society, will pursue a mixed strategy: public objectives, public investments in infrastructure, private investments in industrial transformation, research and development missions based on public-private partnerships, and informed populations.
In fact, it is the most sophisticated industrial policy at its level.
(I recently indicated, in these general terms, what a social-democratic Green New Deal strategy would look like for the United States.)
We have reasons to be optimistic.
The most important point is that advanced technologies, which will enable the creation of a decarbonized, resource-efficient, and therefore ecologically sustainable advanced economy, exist, at the commercial or pre-commercial stage.
In combining renewable energy, digital technologies, cutting-edge materials, and collaborative economies in transport or in other infrastructure, we can de-carbonize the energy system, switch to a circular economy, and drastically reduce primary resource flows.
But to do this, we must overcome three major challenges.
The first is to overcome the interests seeking to maintain the status quo.
The major oil companies will have to absorb the losses, but the workers in the sector and mining regions should receive compensations, in the form of income support, re-skilling through training, and other public aid.
The European plan justifiably claims a "just transition".
The second challenge is that of financing.
Europe, as well as the other regions of the world, will have to redirect a relatively small part of its production, namely 1% to 2%, towards the green economy, particularly with regard to new infrastructure, public markets, research and development, the renewal of industrial equipment, etc. The financing will come from the private sector, but also from public budgets.
Europe must stand up to the ideologues who oppose an increase in EU spending.
Facts will have to be taken into account.
The last major challenge is diplomatic.
Europe accounts for around 9.1% of global carbon dioxide emissions, while China's share is 30% and that of the United States is 14%.
Even if Europe manages to put its green pact in place in its entirety, it will be of little use if other regions of the world do not join it in its fight.
European leaders therefore rightly consider diplomacy to be fundamental to the success of the green pact.
Let us take the example of China.
After decades of rapid growth, which eliminated mass poverty, China has become the world's largest CO2 emitter (although its per capita emissions remain twice those of the United States).
China, on its own, will determine the future of the global climate.
On the one hand, Chinese leaders know that their country is extremely vulnerable to climate change and risks diplomatic isolation if it doesn't make enough efforts to decarbonize; on the other hand, they must face the dangers of the unfortunate cold war launched by America.
The hardliners within the government and Chinese coal lobbies resist, under pressure from the United States, decarbonization, especially since Trump rejects it himself.
European diplomacy can make a difference if it refuses to subscribe to America's insidious measures to hinder China and instead proposes to it a positive and unambiguous partnership: working together to establish sustainable infrastructure, development, and technology in Eurasia, within the framework of a Chinese Green Deal comparable to that of Europe.
Such a partnership would be of immense benefit to Europe, China, and the dozen Eurasian countries that separate them, not to mention the world as a whole.
The Europe has made a historical step with its ambitious, mobilizing and realistic plan.
The Green Deal is a powerful signal of hope in a world of uncertainties and instability.
